    relatedTextRefs: ["Acts 2:1-13", "1 Corinthians 12:4-11", "Mark 16:17-18"],
    layers: {
      accessible:
        "Pentecostalism began on April 9, 1906, at 214 Bonnie Brae Street in Los Angeles, when participants in a prayer meeting led by William Seymour (a Black preacher, son of former slaves) began speaking in tongues. The Azusa Street Revival that followed (1906-1915) drew people of all races and social classes at a time when America was rigidly segregated. Participants believed they were experiencing a 'new Pentecost' -- a fresh outpouring of the Holy Spirit like the one described in Acts 2. Today, Pentecostalism (including Charismatic movements within Catholic, Orthodox, and mainline Protestant churches) claims roughly 650 million adherents worldwide -- about a quarter of all Christians. It is the fastest-growing branch of Christianity in Africa, Latin America, and Asia.",
      intermediate:
        "Core Pentecostal distinctives: 'Baptism in the Holy Spirit' as a second experience after conversion, typically evidenced by speaking in tongues (glossolalia). The continuation of all spiritual gifts (healing, prophecy, miracles, tongues, interpretation of tongues) -- these did not cease with the apostolic age. Lively, participatory worship with expectation of direct divine encounter. Emphasis on personal holiness and the imminent return of Christ.\n\nPentecostalism's growth in the Global South is the most significant development in modern Christianity. In Brazil, roughly 25% of the population is Pentecostal. In Nigeria, Ghana, South Korea, and the Philippines, Pentecostal churches are growing exponentially. The prosperity gospel (the teaching that God rewards faith with financial blessing) has become dominant in many Pentecostal churches, especially in Africa and Latin America. Critics see this as theological manipulation of the poor. Defenders argue it offers hope and agency to marginalized people.\n\nAcademically, Pentecostalism was long dismissed as emotionalism for the uneducated. This has changed dramatically. Amos Yong ('The Spirit Poured Out on All Flesh') and Frank Macchia ('Baptized in the Spirit') have developed sophisticated Pentecostal theologies. The Pentecostal emphasis on experience, embodiment, and the Spirit has influenced theological conversations far beyond Pentecostal circles.",
      advanced:
        "Harvey Cox ('Fire from Heaven') and Allan Anderson ('An Introduction to Pentecostalism') provide the essential global perspectives. Anderson argues that Pentecostalism should be understood not as a single movement but as a family of movements united by the emphasis on the Spirit's power and presence. Its adaptability to local cultures (African indigenous Pentecostalism looks very different from American megachurch Pentecostalism) is the key to its growth.\n\nThe theological significance of Pentecostalism for the broader church is the recovery of pneumatology (theology of the Holy Spirit). Western Christianity (both Catholic and Protestant) has been accused of neglecting the Spirit in favor of Christology and ecclesiology. Pentecostalism's insistence that the Spirit is active, present, and powerful today corrects this imbalance. Whether the specific manifestations (tongues, prophecy, healing) are genuine is debated, but the underlying claim -- that God is not finished acting in the world -- is one that most Christians would affirm in theory, even if Pentecostal practice makes them uncomfortable."
    },
